1
00:00:00,610 --> 00:00:05,770
The doji candle is one of the most famous
patterns followed closely by price action

2
00:00:05,770 --> 00:00:06,770
traders.

3
00:00:06,770 --> 00:00:12,459
A doji candle pattern appears when the open
price and close price for a determined period

4
00:00:12,459 --> 00:00:16,090
are the same, or very close to being the same.

5
00:00:16,090 --> 00:00:19,250
The lengths of the shadows can be different.

6
00:00:19,250 --> 00:00:25,240
The perfect doji has the same open price and
close price, however, something must be considered.

7
00:00:25,240 --> 00:00:31,520
If the difference between the open and close
prices is within a few ticks, this could also

8
00:00:31,520 --> 00:00:34,160
be interpreted as a doji.

9
00:00:34,160 --> 00:00:38,620
When you’re not sure if a candle should
be considered a doji or not, just follow the

10
00:00:38,620 --> 00:00:40,570
recent price action.

11
00:00:40,570 --> 00:00:46,330
If the previous candles had open and close
prices within a few ticks, then probably you

12
00:00:46,330 --> 00:00:49,149
should not consider the current candlestick
as a doji.

13
00:00:49,149 --> 00:00:55,030
If the pattern forms alone, that’s a valid
doji.

14
00:00:55,030 --> 00:01:01,059
In this chart, we see several candlesticks
that could be interpreted as a doji pattern.

15
00:01:01,059 --> 00:01:06,549
But, looking at the bigger picture and at
the price action as a whole, we should not

16
00:01:06,549 --> 00:01:11,360
consider the candles as doji, as they offer
no relevance to the current trend.

17
00:01:11,360 --> 00:01:17,880
As you can see, this interpretation is quite
subjective and there are no strict rules but

18
00:01:17,880 --> 00:01:19,790
to look at recent price action.

19
00:01:19,790 --> 00:01:29,270
A series of very small real bodies as in this
example would not be read as doji candles.

20
00:01:29,270 --> 00:01:33,340
Another technique is based on recent support
and resistance levels.

21
00:01:33,340 --> 00:01:39,100
If the market is at an important market support
or resistance and there are other technical

22
00:01:39,100 --> 00:01:45,670
signals, the appearance of an uncertain doji
candle could be interpreted as a doji.

23
00:01:45,670 --> 00:01:50,410
Looking at this example, we are at an important
level of support, tested several times in

24
00:01:50,410 --> 00:01:51,990
the past.

25
00:01:51,990 --> 00:01:57,810
The highlighted candle could be interpreted
as a doji pattern, as it formed near an important

26
00:01:57,810 --> 00:01:59,220
level.

27
00:01:59,220 --> 00:02:03,280
Now, how to read doji candlestick.

28
00:02:03,280 --> 00:02:06,590
First, doji meaning market indecision.

29
00:02:06,590 --> 00:02:13,060
One of the most important values of a candlestick
chart is the ability to read market sentiment.

30
00:02:13,060 --> 00:02:17,750
A doji candle is the perfect example for reading
market sentiment.

31
00:02:17,750 --> 00:02:21,310
This pattern is an outcome of indecision in
the market.

32
00:02:21,310 --> 00:02:28,040
A doji candlestick suggests a lack of control
in the market either by the bulls or the bears.

33
00:02:28,040 --> 00:02:34,450
The lack of direction is clear: bulls moved
prices higher, bears moved prices lower, but

34
00:02:34,450 --> 00:02:39,620
in the end, the market price closed exactly
or very close to where it opened.

35
00:02:39,620 --> 00:02:45,569
Now, if the doji candle highlights market
indecision, it is safe to say that it does

36
00:02:45,569 --> 00:02:49,340
not offer insight into whether bulls or bears
are in control.

37
00:02:49,340 --> 00:02:52,670
You have to guess the market’s next direction.

38
00:02:52,670 --> 00:02:58,030
So, the first thing you should take note is
to use doji candle in combination with other

39
00:02:58,030 --> 00:03:04,510
technical indicators or price action, never
on its own.

40
00:03:04,510 --> 00:03:08,040
Doji candle meaning possible reversal.

41
00:03:08,040 --> 00:03:13,550
Doji candle offers traders an early warning
that there may be a change in market momentum

42
00:03:13,550 --> 00:03:17,050
or a possible change in direction if current
conditions don’t change.

43
00:03:17,050 --> 00:03:22,690
Please remember that the “possibility”
of a change of direction does not represent

44
00:03:22,690 --> 00:03:25,340
a guaranteed change of direction.

45
00:03:25,340 --> 00:03:28,599
The truth is that we don’t know if a trend
is exhausted.

46
00:03:28,599 --> 00:03:32,090
We don’t know the exact moment when the
trend is going to end.

47
00:03:32,090 --> 00:03:38,560
A doji will not guarantee that a certain setup
will occur or that the market will reverse.

48
00:03:38,560 --> 00:03:43,760
Traders incorporate doji in their analysis
in an effort to try to predict future price

49
00:03:43,760 --> 00:03:44,760
movements.

50
00:03:44,760 --> 00:03:48,900
They try to get the probabilities in their
favor as much as they possibly can.

51
00:03:48,900 --> 00:03:54,891
So, a doji candle by itself is not significant
enough to predict a reversal in prices, it

52
00:03:54,891 --> 00:03:59,209
represents only a warning of an impending
trend change.

53
00:03:59,209 --> 00:04:06,379
Steve Nilson, the person that introduced candlesticks
to western traders, affirmed that doji candles

54
00:04:06,379 --> 00:04:11,379
tend to be better at indicating a change in
trend when they occur at market highs instead

55
00:04:11,379 --> 00:04:13,470
of at market lows.

56
00:04:13,470 --> 00:04:18,159
This could be explained by the fact that for
an uptrend to continue, new buying power must

57
00:04:18,159 --> 00:04:24,119
be present on the market, while a downtrend
could continue at full strength without becoming

58
00:04:24,119 --> 00:04:26,869
weaker.

59
00:04:26,869 --> 00:04:33,689
Doji pattern near support and resistance
Doji candles formed at relevant market highs

60
00:04:33,689 --> 00:04:38,580
or lows can sometimes turn into support or
resistance areas.

61
00:04:38,580 --> 00:04:45,020
When forms in the middle of a trend or trading
range, a doji candle has little significance.

62
00:04:45,020 --> 00:04:50,819
Doji candles are commonly met during periods
of consolidation and can help traders to spot

63
00:04:50,819 --> 00:04:53,189
potential price breakouts.

64
00:04:53,189 --> 00:04:58,460
When it forms near round numbers or around
previous levels of support and resistance,

65
00:04:58,460 --> 00:05:04,680
pivot points or Fibonacci retracements, doji
candles offer traders decent entry points.

66
00:05:04,680 --> 00:05:10,889
There are five different types of doji candles:
The first type is the common doji.

67
00:05:10,889 --> 00:05:14,840
A common doji is the candlestick pattern we
talked before.

68
00:05:14,840 --> 00:05:20,639
A doji candle pattern appears when the open
price and close price for a determined period

69
00:05:20,639 --> 00:05:24,689
are the same, or very close to being the same.

70
00:05:24,689 --> 00:05:26,319
Next we have the gravestone doji.

71
00:05:26,319 --> 00:05:33,479
A gravestone doji forms when the doji is at,
or very near, the low of the period.

72
00:05:33,479 --> 00:05:40,020
As the upper shadow is quite long, this means
that the gravestone doji is a bearish pattern.

73
00:05:40,020 --> 00:05:45,930
The bearish outlook of the pattern is evident:
the price opened and traded higher all the

74
00:05:45,930 --> 00:05:51,669
period, but closed where it opened, which
also coincides with the low price for the

75
00:05:51,669 --> 00:05:52,669
period.

76
00:05:52,669 --> 00:05:57,879
Gravestone doji can also be interpreted as
a failed rally.

77
00:05:57,879 --> 00:06:01,379
Traded by itself, this pattern is not profitable.

78
00:06:01,379 --> 00:06:05,629
Just look at the picture above, the price
indeed declined after the appearance of a

79
00:06:05,629 --> 00:06:10,470
gravestone doji, but not before taking some
stop-losses on its way.

80
00:06:10,470 --> 00:06:16,219
That’s why it’s better to trade this pattern
near strong support and resistance levels

81
00:06:16,219 --> 00:06:20,360
and in combination with other indicators.

82
00:06:20,360 --> 00:06:23,020
Then we have the dragonfly doji.

83
00:06:23,020 --> 00:06:28,770
The dragonfly doji forms when the open price
and close price are at the high of the period.

84
00:06:28,770 --> 00:06:35,900
As this pattern has a long lower shadow this
means that dragonfly doji is a bullish pattern.

85
00:06:35,900 --> 00:06:41,139
The bullish outlook of the pattern could be
explained as follows: the price opened and

86
00:06:41,139 --> 00:06:47,529
traded lower all the period, but closed where
it opened, which also coincides with the high

87
00:06:47,529 --> 00:06:49,409
price for the period.

88
00:06:49,409 --> 00:06:54,729
This means that despite the selling pressure,
the bulls entered the market strong and pushed

89
00:06:54,729 --> 00:06:56,690
the price back up.

90
00:06:56,690 --> 00:07:02,889
As in the case of gravestone doji, this pattern
is not profitable when traded by itself.

91
00:07:02,889 --> 00:07:08,309
If we look at the picture above, the dragonfly
doji pattern formed near an important level

92
00:07:08,309 --> 00:07:11,729
of support, which indeed drove the price higher.

93
00:07:11,729 --> 00:07:16,439
That’s why it’s important to trade this
pattern near strong support and resistance

94
00:07:16,439 --> 00:07:21,839
levels and in combination with other tools.

95
00:07:21,839 --> 00:07:24,800
Next type is the long-legged doji.

96
00:07:24,800 --> 00:07:30,459
The long-legged doji has long upper and lower
shadows in the middle of the period’s trading

97
00:07:30,459 --> 00:07:34,879
range, reflecting the indecision of buyers
and sellers.

98
00:07:34,879 --> 00:07:40,909
Throughout the period, the market moved higher
and then sharply lower, or vice versa.

99
00:07:40,909 --> 00:07:44,860
It then closed at or very near the opening
price.

100
00:07:44,860 --> 00:07:50,399
This signals market indecision, as neither
the bulls nor the bears won the battle.

101
00:07:50,399 --> 00:07:55,249
From my experience long-legged doji candles
will offer many false signals and should only

102
00:07:55,249 --> 00:08:01,379
be traded on higher time frames and in combination
with other technical tools.

103
00:08:01,379 --> 00:08:04,270
The last type is the rare doji.

104
00:08:04,270 --> 00:08:10,300
The rare doji occurs the open, high, low,
and close of the price are all the same.

105
00:08:10,300 --> 00:08:16,239
This pattern forms when a market is very illiquid
or the data source did not have any prices

106
00:08:16,239 --> 00:08:18,360
other than the close.

107
00:08:18,360 --> 00:08:23,129
The rare doji pattern should be interpreted
as a complete and total uncertainty in the

108
00:08:23,129 --> 00:08:25,060
market direction.

109
00:08:25,060 --> 00:08:29,639
Now, this is how I trade the doji.

110
00:08:29,639 --> 00:08:34,490
Like I said before, I always take trades only
around support and resistance areas.

111
00:08:34,490 --> 00:08:41,509
You can use recent market swings or fib retracements,
but I prefer to use pivot points.

112
00:08:41,509 --> 00:08:48,000
This chart shows the exact sequence we need:
a doji formed around a pivot point level.

113
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:54,310
The next one to three candles after a doji
forms must close above the high of that doji

114
00:08:54,310 --> 00:08:55,310
candle.

115
00:08:55,310 --> 00:08:59,120
That is the key; the close is the confirmation
that a bullish transition took place.

116
00:08:59,120 --> 00:09:05,449
So in this pattern, we are looking for a specific
conditional change to take place in the market,

117
00:09:05,449 --> 00:09:12,180
namely, a higher closing high above a doji’s
high, but must occur near a pivot point level.

118
00:09:12,180 --> 00:09:17,459
That’s the most important part of this setup
which will help to eliminate and filter out

119
00:09:17,459 --> 00:09:19,190
false signals.

120
00:09:19,190 --> 00:09:23,949
Initially, use stop below the low of the doji.

121
00:09:23,949 --> 00:09:29,470
Once the market begins to produce a profit
and moves in the desired direction, then you

122
00:09:29,470 --> 00:09:32,470
can change it or continually trail the stop.

123
00:09:32,470 --> 00:09:38,110
If you don’t like to trade 100% price action,
you can also use a “filter” or backup

124
00:09:38,110 --> 00:09:45,170
process to confirm the buy signal with other
indicator (stochastic, moving average, whatever

125
00:09:45,170 --> 00:09:47,149
you prefer)

126
00:09:47,149 --> 00:09:52,889
Here is another example, on a 15-minute chart
on the British pound US dollar.

127
00:09:52,889 --> 00:09:58,360
Once we added our pivot points, we have our
first area of interest here.

128
00:09:58,360 --> 00:10:03,899
As you can see, the market traded around the
pivot level and a doji pattern formed.

129
00:10:03,899 --> 00:10:08,730
He have a close above the doji’s high.

130
00:10:08,730 --> 00:10:15,490
Also note that the market closed above the
moving-average which is also bullish.

131
00:10:15,490 --> 00:10:22,180
Once we have a close above the high of the
doji, we can start searching for long entries.

132
00:10:22,180 --> 00:10:29,560
To summarize, when you identify a doji at
or near the pivot level, wait for confirmation

133
00:10:29,560 --> 00:10:34,529
of the next candle to close above the doji’s
high.

134
00:10:34,529 --> 00:10:57,100
Here are other examples of trades, using doji
patterns around pivot levels.

135
00:10:57,100 --> 00:11:02,040
Looking at these examples, i hope you noticed
that I prefer to consider doji candles as

136
00:11:02,040 --> 00:11:07,340
accumulation zones where bull or bears are
gaining momentum for a continuation of the

137
00:11:07,340 --> 00:11:08,340
main trend.

138
00:11:08,340 --> 00:11:14,589
I’m not chasing reversals like most of traders,
I’m looking for continuation patterns.

139
00:11:14,589 --> 00:11:20,120
And I always combine this doji pattern with
other technical tools, to confirm the main

140
00:11:20,120 --> 00:11:22,160
trend.

141
00:11:22,160 --> 00:11:25,342
If you got any value from this and learned
something new, don’t forget to subscribe,

142
00:11:25,342 --> 00:11:29,399
hit the bell icon and leave us a like to show
your support.

143
00:11:29,399 --> 00:11:29,800
Until next time.

